definition: filled to capacity (of theater, stadium, gymnasium etc)
to explode or burst/to quick fry or quick boil
Manchu ethnic group
to fill/full/filled/packed/fully/completely/quite/to reach the limit/to satisfy/satisfied/contented

sentences.english: In Massachusetts, homeless shelters are at capacity.
sentences.chinese: 马萨诸塞州的收容所已经爆满。

sentences.english: And it's always crowded,  so the food is always really fresh.
sentences.chinese: 而且那的人总是爆满，所以食物总是新鲜的。

sentences.english: But still, the booths were packed.
All the hotels and restaurants will be crowded.
sentences.chinese: 所有的餐馆和旅馆都会爆满。

sentences.english: Your groom is made of mahogany, and his drawer is full of silver plates.
sentences.chinese: 你的新郎是红木制成，和他的抽屉是银盘子爆满。

sentences.english: Click on and take note of the cardboard boxes full of office supplies on walkway to the castle.
sentences.chinese: 点击并注意在纸箱上行人路与城堡的办公用品爆满。

sentences.english: As the ads run, customers flood the call center.
sentences.chinese: 随着广告的播出，呼叫中心顾客爆满。

sentences.english: I guess the hotels will all be full.
sentences.chinese: 我猜那时候旅馆会爆满的。

sentences.english: Despite the weather is not good, the guests in the opera house still full.
sentences.chinese: 尽管天气不好，但歌剧院里的客人依然爆满。

sentences.english: Sold-out arenas were the just the tip of the iceberg, Pastuszek believes.
sentences.chinese: 帕斯图斯泽克相信，球馆爆满仅仅只是冰山一角。

sentences.english: The workshop was filled within 24 hours and there was a waiting list.
sentences.chinese: 工作坊24小时爆满，此外还有很多人在等待。

sentences.english: The new adaptation played to full-houses for ten nights in June.
sentences.chinese: 这部剧在六月份演出的时候，十个晚上都是场场爆满。

sentences.english: The restaurant is usually full on friday evening.
sentences.chinese: 这家外馆星期五晚上总是爆满。

sentences.english: It went from smaller venues to sold-out arenas in a matter of months.
sentences.chinese: 先是在小场地举办，后来发展到每场爆满的大舞台。

sentences.english: We hope the stadium will be packed.
sentences.chinese: 我们希望体育场届时能爆满。

lit. a banquet with no empty seats/full house/capacity crowd/standing room only
to have a full house/to be sold out/no vacancy
to form a long queue (idiom)/(of cars) to be bumper to bumper
fully booked/every seat taken
multitude/vast crowd
front yard as busy as a marketplace (idiom)/a place with many visitors
crowded to bursting point/filled to overflowing/jam-packed
brim full/completely packed
to come to a place on account of its reputation (idiom); attracted to visit a famous location
to reserve all the seats (or a large block of seats) at a theater, restaurant etc
lit. not one drop can trickle through (idiom); fig. impenetrable (crowd, traffic)
lit. a boiling cauldron of voices (idiom)/hubbub/brouhaha
overcrowded/jam-packed
full complement/at full strength/no vacancies
you can net sparrows at the door (idiom); completely deserted
